Ex[3] - Programming Interactive Data Visualisation with R

Published

January 28, 2023

Modified

March 24, 2023

1. OVERVIEW

In this exercise, learn how to create :

  • interactive data visualisation by using ggiraph and plotlyr packages,

  • animated data visualisation by using gganimate and plotlyr packages.

  • Visualising univariate data with large number of categories by using rPackedBar package.

  • reshape data by using tidyr package.

  • process, wrangle and transform data by using dplyr package.

2. R PACKAGE REQUIRED

2.1 Load R Packages

Usage of the code chunk below :

p_load( ) - pacman - to load packages into R environment. This function will attempt to install the package from CRAN or pacman repository list if it is not installed.

pacman::p_load(ggiraph, plotly, gganimate, DT, tidyverse, patchwork, gapminder, rPackedBar)
Usage of R Packages :

  • ggiraph for making ‘ggplot’ graphics interactive.

  • plotly, R library for plotting interactive statistical graphs.

  • gganimate, an ggplot extension for creating animated statistical graphs.

  • DT provides an R interface to the JavaScript library DataTables that create interactive table on html page.

  • tidyverse, a family of modern R packages specially designed to support data science, analysis and communication task including creating static statistical graphs.

  • patchwork for compising multiple plots.

3. DATA PREPARATION

3.1 Acquire Data Source

This study will be based on fictitious data set provided with this lesson.

3.2 Import Data

3.2.1 Import Data

Involved two (2) steps : import and inspect imported data set.

Usage of the code chunk below :

read_csv( ) - readr - to read CSV file into a tibble.

problems( ) - readr - to reveal any parsing errors when importing the CSV file.

exam_data <- read_csv("data/Exam_data.csv")

problems(exam_data)
# A tibble: 0 × 5
# ℹ 5 variables: row <int>, col <int>, expected <chr>, actual <chr>, file <chr>

4 METHOD :: ggiraph package

4.1 Tooltip

4.1.1 Create ggplot Object

Usage of the code chunk below :

geom_dotplot_interactive( ) - ggplot2 - to plot interactive dot chart.

Show the code 
p <- ggplot(data = exam_data,
            aes(x = MATHS)) +
  geom_dotplot_interactive(aes(tooltip = ID),
                           stackgroups = TRUE,
                           binwidth = 1,
                           method = "histodot") +
  scale_y_continuous(NULL,
                     breaks = NULL)

4.1.2 create interactive svg Object

Show the code 
girafe(ggobj = p,
       width_svg = 6,
       height_svg = 6*0.618)
